1. What is polymorphism in Java?
-->Polymorphism means “many forms.”
    In Java, one method or object can behave differently in different situations.
    
    Types:
    Compile-time polymorphism → Method Overloading
    Runtime polymorphism → Method Overriding
    Example
    class Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Animal sound");
        }
    }
    
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Dog barks");
        }
    }



2. What is the difference between compile-time/early binding/static polymorphism and runtime/late binding/dynamic polymorphism?
-->
| Compile-time Polymorphism            | Runtime Polymorphism             |
| ------------------------------------ | -------------------------------- |
| Achieved using method overloading    | Achieved using method overriding |
| Method call resolved at compile time | Method call resolved at runtime  |
| Also called static binding           | Also called dynamic binding      |
| Faster                               | Slightly slower                  |

2B. why compile time polymorphism is called early binding and runtime polymorphism is called late binding ?explainin in simple
-->To understand these terms simply, think of "binding" as matching a specific question (a line of code calling a function) to its exact 
    answer (the actual code block that runs)
    The difference between early and late binding comes down entirely to when this matching happens.
    ⏳ Compile-Time Polymorphism (Early Binding)
        Early binding is called "early" because the compiler matches the function call to its definition early in the process
            How it works: This happens during Method Overloading—when you have multiple functions with the exact same name but different input 
                parameters (e.g., add(int a, int b) vs add(double a, double b)).
            The Reason: Because the input types are written directly in the code, the compiler can look at your line of code, count the arguments, and 
                know exactly which function you want immediately. It permanently "binds" the connection right then and there.
            Real-world Analogy: Imagine ordering a meal from a fixed menu. You point directly to "Combo #1" while placing your order. The cashier
                knows exactly what to prepare before you even take a seat.
    
    🚀 Runtime Polymorphism (Late Binding)Late binding is called "late" because the matching is delayed until the very last moment, which is while the
        program is actively running.
            How it works: This happens during Method Overriding and inheritance—when a child class rewrites a method belonging to a parent class 
                    (e.g., a parent Animal class has a makeSound() method, and a child Dog class overrides it to bark).
            The Reason: In your code, you might use a generic parent reference variable to hold a child object (like Animal myPet = getAnimalFromUser();).
                    The compiler has no way of knowing what the user will choose ahead of time. The computer must wait until runtime to see what actual 
                    object is sitting in memory before it can decide which method to trigger.
            Real-world Analogy: Imagine going to a buffet. You ask the chef for the "Daily Special." The chef cannot prepare it until you show up and 
                    choose whether you want the vegetarian or meat option that day.



3. How does method overloading achieve compile-time polymorphism?
-->Method overloading means multiple methods with the same name but different parameters.

Compiler decides which method to call during compilation.

Example
class MathOperation {

    void add(int a, int b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }

    void add(double a, double b) {
        System.out.println(a + b);
    }
}




4. How does method overriding achieve runtime polymorphism?
-->Method overriding occurs when subclass provides its own implementation of superclass method.
    
    Method call is decided at runtime based on object type.
    
    Example
    class Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Animal sound");
        }
    }
    
    class Dog extends Animal {
        void sound() {
            System.out.println("Dog barks");
        }
    }
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Animal a = new Dog();
            a.sound();
        }
    }
    Output
    Dog barks



5. What is dynamic method dispatch in Java, and how does the JVM resolve method calls at runtime?
-->Dynamic method dispatch in Java is the process by which a call to an overridden method is resolved at runtime rather than compile
    time, also known as Runtime Polymorphism. Using a superclass reference to hold a subclass object, the JVM decides which method version 
    to execute based on the actual object type, not the reference type.
   Example:
      Animal a = new Dog();
      a.sound();


6. What is method hiding in Java? Why static methods cannot participate in runtime polymorphism?
-->When subclass defines a static method with same name as superclass static method, it is called method hiding.
    Static methods belong to class, not objects.
    Therefore they are resolved at compile time.
    
    Example
    class A {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("A");
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        static void show() {
            System.out.println("B");
        }
    }


7. What is the role of @Override annotation?
-->@Override tells compiler that method is intended to override superclass method.
    If method does not actually override, compiler gives error.
    Example:
      @Override
      void display() {
      }
      
      Benefits:
        Improves readability
        Prevents mistakes


8. What are the rules to override a method?
-->Method name must be same
    Parameters must be same
    Return type should be same or covariant
    Access modifier cannot be more restrictive
    Final methods cannot be overridden
    Static methods cannot be overridden
    Private methods cannot be overridden



9. What is covariant return type?
-->Covariant return type in Java means that when a subclass overrides a method of the superclass, the overridden method can return a 
    subclass type instead of the superclass return type.

    parent method returns parent type
    
    child overridden method returns child type
    Example:
    class Animal { }
    
    class Dog extends Animal { }
    
    class A {
        Animal get() {
            return new Animal();
        }
    }
    
    class B extends A {
        Dog get() {
            return new Dog();
        }
    }



10. Rules for method overloading in Java?
-->Method name must be same
    Parameters must differ
    Return type alone cannot overload method
    Can change number/type/order of parameters
    Valid Example
    void add(int a)
    void add(int a, int b)
    void add(double a, double b)



11. What is upcasting and downcasting? Why is downcasting risky?
-->Upcasting   
    Converting child object into parent reference.
    
    Animal a = new Dog();
    Downcasting
    
    Converting parent reference back to child reference.
    
    Dog d = (Dog) a;
    Why risky?
    
    Wrong downcasting causes ClassCastException.



12. Can final, static, or private methods be overridden in Java?
-->
| Method Type | Can Override?           |
| ----------- | ----------------------- |
| final       | No                      |
| static      | No (method hiding only) |
| private     | No                      |


13. Can main() be overridden?
-->No, because main() is static.
    Static methods cannot participate in runtime polymorphism.


14. Why constructors cannot be overridden?
-->Constructors cannot be overridden because they are not inherited by subclasses, and overriding requires inheritance. 
    Additionally, constructors run during object creation before polymorphism is active, whereas overriding depends on runtime
    polymorphism. A subclass can only use super()` to chain constructors, not redefine them.


15. Can we override default methods in an interface?
-->Yes.
    Classes implementing interface can override default methods.
    
    Example
    interface A {
        default void show() {
            System.out.println("A");
        }
    }
    
    class B implements A {
        public void show() {
            System.out.println("B");
        }
    }



16. Can overloading be based on access modifiers?
-->No.....overloaded methods do not need to have the same access modifiers.

17. Can a subclass use a different access modifier when overriding a superclass method? Explain with an example.
-->Yes, but visibility can only be increased, not reduced.
    
    Example:
        class A {
            protected void show() {
                System.out.println("A");
            }
        }
        
        class B extends A {
            public void show() {
                System.out.println("B");
            }
        }

    Invalid Example:
        class A {
            public void show() {}
        }
        
        class B extends A {
            protected void show() {} // Error
        }
